The **comparison operator `==`** in Java is used to check whether two values are equal. When used in an `if-else` statement, it allows the program to execute different blocks of code based on whether the condition evaluates to `true` or `false`.

**Syntax:**
```java
if (value1 == value2) {
    // Code to execute if the values are equal
} else {
    // Code to execute if the values are not equal
}
```
- If `value1` is **equal** to `value2`, the `if` block executes.
- If `value1` is **not equal** to `value2`, the `else` block executes.

---
**Example**
```java
import java.util.*;

// Main class
class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Declaring an integer variable
        int number = 10;

        // Checking if the number is equal to 10
        if (number == 10) {
            System.out.println("The number is exactly 10."); // Executes if condition is true
        } else {
            System.out.println("The number is not 10."); // Executes if condition is false
        }

        // This statement executes regardless of the condition
        System.out.println("Comparison check completed.");
    }
}

```

**Output**
```default
The number is exactly 10.
Comparison check completed.
```

